{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521759"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:36:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:36:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13743"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13743","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13743"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.5,0.09,0.22,0.16,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6362"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47195"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6362"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13743"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31916"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"1046"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1197"},{"type":"tags","id":"1356"},{"type":"tags","id":"1393"},{"type":"tags","id":"2118"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2587"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"2873"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"5789"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11834"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12198"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12262"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16696"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42918"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43440"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47195","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47195"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old woman presents to her GP with the primary complaint of a self-described common cold that she has had for many weeks. She describes rhinorrhoea and nasal congestion, cough, facial pain, and has had repeated episodes of epistaxis. On further questioning, she admits to fatigue, anorexia, myalgias, arthralgias and dyspnoea, which she attributes to her illness. Concerningly, however, she notes a recent episode of haemoptysis which prompted her to present to her GP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her vital signs are within normal range. Cardiorespiratory examination is normal, however upon closer inspection of the patient, a palpable purpuric rash is evident over bilateral lower extremities. Multiple ulcers are also evident over the patient\u0027s tongue and palate. Blood tests reveal an elevated CRP and ESR, and an FBE shows a mild normocytic anaemia, but is otherwise normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Granulomatosis with polyangiitis","Polyarteritis nodosa","Eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis","Beh\u00e7et\u0027s disease","Takayasu arteritis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EGranulomatosis with polyangiitis\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E (previously \u0027Wegener granulomatosis\u0027) is a small-medium vessel necrotizing vasculitis that commonly manifests with upper respiratory symptoms, including frequent sinusitis and epistaxis. Less common symptoms may include scleritis, chronic ear infections, hearing loss, purpura, arthralgias and lower tract respiratory symptoms (i.e. cough, dyspnoea, haemoptysis). Renal involvement is relatively uncommon at the time of presentation, but the majority of patients develop glomerulonephritis within 2 years of disease onset. Pulmonary infiltrates and/or nodules are frequently seen on imaging (most often on a high-resolution CT chest). GPA is the most likely explanation for this patient\u0027s symptoms, and thus, is the correct answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolyarteritis nodosa (PAN) \u003C/strong\u003Eis a small- or medium-vessel necrotising vasculitis that can present cutaneously or systemically. It is usually idiopathic but may be secondary to other conditions, such as Hepatitis B or C. As with other vasculitides, PAN commonly causes constitutional symptoms, myalgias, arthralgias, cutaneous ulcers and nodules. PAN can affect any organ but has a predilection for the nervous system (resulting in mononeuritis multiplex or an asymmetric neuropathy), kidneys (leading to hypertension, oliguria and renal failure) and gastrointestinal tract (causing abdominal pain, malabsorption and abdominal aortic aneurysms). It is not the most likely differential in this patient, as the patient has upper airway involvement (as evidenced by sinusitis, epistaxis and haemoptysis) which is markedly more common in GPA than PAN.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis\u003C/strong\u003E (previously \u0027Churg-Strauss syndrome\u0027) is a small-medium vessel necrotising vasculitis that is associated with asthma, rhinosinusitis, neuropathy, pulmonary involvement and eosinophilia in the blood or extravascular eosinophils in the tissue. 4 out of 6 features are required for diagnosis. Given the absence of peripheral blood eosinophilia, asthma and neuropathy symptoms, there are insufficient symptoms to meet the diagnosis, and thus it is incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBe\u00e7het\u0027s disease \u003C/strong\u003Eis an auto-inflammatory systemic variable vessel vasculitis with an unknown aetiology, characterised by recurrent, painful oral and genital ulcers. Other manifestations may include pathergy (papulopustules that form at the site of a needle injury within 1-2 days), ophthalmic lesions (e.g. uveitis, scleritis), fatigue, fibromyalgia, arthritis and vascular involvement. Although this patient has oral ulcers and constitutional symptoms, the upper respiratory symptoms are more in keeping with GPA, and thus Be\u00e7het\u0027s disease is not the most likely differential diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETakayasu arteritis \u003C/strong\u003Eis a medium- and large-vessel vasculitis. As with other vasculitides, it typically presents with constitutional symptoms. However, as the larger arteries are affected, symptoms result from arterial insufficiency, such as hypertension (due to renovascular stenosis), upper limb claudication (due to upper extremity ischaemia secondary to stenosis) and neurological symptoms (due to carotid artery occlusion). As this patient is not hypertensive, and lacks neurological symptoms or signs of upper limb claudication, Takayasu arteritis is not the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Granulomatosis with polyangiitis is a small-vessel vasculitis that commonly causes constitutional symptoms and upper respiratory involvement"],"references":["Greco A, Marinelli C, Fusconi M, et al. Clinic manifestations in granulomatosis with polyangiitis. International Journal of Immunopathology and Pharmacology. 2016;29(2):151-159.","Fagni F, Bello F, Emmi G. Eosinophilic Granulomatosis With Polyangiitis: Dissecting the Pathophysiology. Front Med (Lausanne). 2021 Feb 24;8:627776."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31916"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13743"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31916"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-17T16:07:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-08T21:38:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"it